# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: purdue-model
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:purdue-model/defense-in-depth-computing] The idea behind the defense in depth approach is to defend a system against any particular attack using several independent methods.
[src:purdue-model/defense-in-depth-computing] It is a layering tactic, conceived by the National Security Agency (NSA) as a comprehensive approach to information and electronic security.
[src:purdue-model/defense-in-depth-computing] Defense in depth is sometimes thought of as forming the layers of an onion, with data at the core of the onion, people the next outer layer of the onion, and network security, host-based security, and application security forming the outermost layers of the onion.
[src:purdue-model/defense-in-depth-computing] Defense in depth can be divided into three overarching areas: Physical, Technical, and Administrative.
[src:purdue-model/defense-in-depth-computing] Physical controls are anything that physically limits or prevents access to IT systems.
[src:purdue-model/defense-in-depth-computing] Examples of physical defensive security are: fences, guards, dogs, and CCTV systems.
[src:purdue-model/defense-in-depth-computing] Technical controls are hardware or software whose purpose is to protect systems and resources.
[src:purdue-model/defense-in-depth-computing] Examples of technical controls include disk encryption, file integrity software, authentication, network security controls, antiviruses, and behavioural analysis software.
[src:purdue-model/defense-in-depth-computing] In the event that one layer of defence fails, defense in depth aims to ensure network security via a second-line of defence.
[src:purdue-model/defense-in-depth-computing] For example, if an attacker penetrates a computer system at a given OSI layer (e.g.
[src:purdue-model/defense-in-depth-computing] Layer 3), a redundancy should exist at another layer (Layer 7) to ensure layered defense.
[src:purdue-model/defense-in-depth-computing] Administrative controls are the organization's policies and procedures and govern the organisation's human resources, technology, and operations.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] The finance module in particular is essential to a suite of applications meeting the definition of an ERP system.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] The finance module provides the **system of record** for the organisation; recording the commercial impact of the business operations in the General Ledger.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP provides an integrated and continuously updated view of core business processes, typically using a shared database managed by a database management system.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems track business resources—cash, raw materials, production capacity—and the status of business commitments: orders, purchase orders, and payroll.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] The applications that make up the system share data across various departments (manufacturing, purchasing, sales, accounting, etc.) that provide the data.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP facilitates information flow between all business functions and manages connections to outside stakeholders.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Estimates of the size of the global ERP market range between USD $78 and $81 billion in 2026 .
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Though early ERP systems focused on large enterprises, smaller enterprises increasingly use ERP systems.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] The ERP system integrates varied organizational systems and facilitates error-free transactions and production, thereby enhancing the organization's efficiency.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] However, developing an ERP system differs from traditional system development.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems run on a variety of computer hardware and network configurations, typically using a database as an information repository.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Business and technology research and advisory firm Gartner is credited for first using the acronym ERP in the 1990s.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] The term captured a functional extension of two manufacturing-based concepts, material requirements planning (MRP) and manufacturing resource planning (MRP II).
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Without replacing these terms, ERP came to represent a larger whole that reflected the evolution of application integration beyond manufacturing.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Not all ERP packages are developed from a manufacturing core; ERP vendors variously began assembling their packages with finance-and-accounting, maintenance, and human-resource components.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] By the mid-1990s ERP systems addressed all core enterprise functions.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Governments and non–profit organizations also began to use ERP systems.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] An "ERP system selection methodology" is a formal process for selecting an enterprise resource planning (ERP) system.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Existing methodologies include: Kuiper's funnel method, Dobrin's three-dimensional (3D) web-based decision support tool, and the Clarkston Potomac methodology.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems experienced rapid growth in the 1990s.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Because of the year 2000 problem many companies took the opportunity to replace their old systems with ERP.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems initially focused on automating back office functions that did not directly affect customers and the public.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Front office functions, such as customer relationship management (CRM), dealt directly with customers, or e-business systems such as e-commerce and e-government—or supplier relationship management (SRM) became integrated later, when the internet simplified communicating with external parties.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] "ERP II" was coined in 2000 in an article by Gartner Publications entitled *ERP Is Dead—Long Live ERP II*.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] It describes web–based software that provides real–time access to ERP systems to employees and partners (such as suppliers and customers).
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] The ERP II role expands traditional ERP resource optimization and transaction processing.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Rather than just manage buying, selling, etc.—ERP II leverages information in the resources under its management to help the enterprise collaborate with other enterprises.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP II is more flexible than the first generation ERP.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Rather than confine ERP system capabilities within the organization, it goes beyond the corporate walls to interact with other systems.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Enterprise application suite is an alternate name for such systems.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP II systems are typically used to enable collaborative initiatives such as supply chain management (SCM), customer relationship management (CRM) and business intelligence (BI) among business partner organizations through the use of various electronic business technologies.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] The large proportion of companies are pursuing a strong managerial targets in ERP system instead of acquire an ERP company.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Developers now make more effort to integrate mobile devices with the ERP system.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP vendors are extending ERP to these devices, along with other business applications, so that businesses don't have to rely on third-party applications.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] As an example, the e-commerce platform Shopify was able to make ERP tools from Microsoft and Oracle available on its app in October 2021.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Technical stakes of modern ERP concern integration—hardware, applications, networking, supply chains.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP now covers more functions and roles—including decision making, stakeholders' relationships, standardization, transparency, globalization, etc.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] From 1999 the ERP industry underwent a paradigm shift from the existing on-premise model (i.e. separate installations of the ERP system on the client's or third-party servers) to cloud (i.e. the ERP system is served to the user via a web browser with all of it's components hosted in data centres).
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] This followed the launch of early pure cloud ERP systems such as NetLedger.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] This shift required massive technology and business model changes from the ERP vendors.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] An ERP system covers the following common functional areas.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Government resource planning (GRP) is the equivalent of an ERP for the public sector and an integrated office automation system for government bodies.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] The software structure, modularization, core algorithms and main interfaces do not differ from other ERPs, and ERP software suppliers manage to adapt their systems to government agencies.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Most ERP systems incorporate best practices.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] This means the software reflects the vendor's interpretation of the most effective way to perform each business process.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Systems vary in how conveniently the customer can modify these practices.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Use of best practices eases compliance with requirements such as International Financial Reporting Standards, Sarbanes–Oxley, or Basel II.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] They can also help comply with de facto industry standards, such as electronic funds transfer.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] This is because the procedure can be readily codified within the ERP software and replicated with confidence across multiple businesses that share that business requirement.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems connect to real–time data and transaction data in a variety of ways.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] These systems are typically configured by systems integrators, who bring unique knowledge on process, equipment, and vendor solutions.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP's scope usually implies significant changes to staff work processes and practices.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Generally, three types of services are available to help implement such changes: consulting, customization, and support.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Implementation time depends on business size, number of modules, customization, the scope of process changes, and the readiness of the customer to take ownership for the project.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Modular ERP systems can be implemented in stages.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] The typical project for a large enterprise takes about 14 months and requires around 150 consultants.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Small projects can require months; multinational and other large implementations can take years.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Customization can substantially increase implementation times.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Besides that, information processing influences various business functions e.g. some large corporations like Walmart use a just in time inventory system.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] This reduces inventory storage and increases delivery efficiency, and requires up-to-date data.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Before 2014, Walmart used a system called Inforem developed by IBM to manage replenishment.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] The outcome of the implementation process will be significantly impacted by the skills and experience of the implementing team combined with a tried and tested implementation methodology that provides guardrails to drive the project to success.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP implementations are a specific sub-type of project however there is no industry-specified standard methodology.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Implementation methodologies are created by the ERP vendors or the specialist ERP consulting firms, generally known as Value Added Resellers (VARs), who carry out the implementations.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Each implementer's methodology can be assessed as to how well it meets the principles and practices outlined in the guides of the project management peak industry bodies such as Project Management Institute.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Implementing ERP typically requires changes in existing business processes.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Poor understanding of needed process changes prior to starting implementation is a main reason for project failure.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] The difficulties could be related to the system, business process, infrastructure, training, or lack of motivation.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] It is therefore crucial that organizations thoroughly analyze processes before they deploy an ERP software.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Analysis can identify opportunities for process modernization.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] It also enables an assessment of the alignment of current processes with those provided by the ERP system.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP implementation is considerably more difficult (and politically charged) in decentralized organizations, because they often have different processes, business rules, data semantics, authorization hierarchies, and decision centers.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] This may require migrating some business units before others, delaying implementation to work through the necessary changes for each unit, possibly reducing integration (e.g., linking via master data management) or customizing the system to meet specific needs.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] A potential disadvantage is that adopting "standard" processes can lead to a loss of competitive advantage.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] While this has happened, losses in one area are often offset by gains in other areas, increasing overall competitive advantage.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Configuring an ERP system is largely a matter of balancing the way the organization wants the system to work, and the way the system is designed to work out of the box.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems typically include many configurable settings that in effect modify system operations.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] For example, in the ServiceNow platform, business rules can be written requiring the signature of a business owner within 2 weeks of a newly completed risk assessment.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] The tool can be configured to automatically email notifications to the business owner, and transition the risk assessment to various stages in the process depending on the owner's responses or lack thereof.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Two-tier ERP software and hardware lets companies run the equivalent of two ERP systems at once: one at the corporate level and one at the division or subsidiary level.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] For example, a manufacturing company could use an ERP system to manage across the organization using independent global or regional distribution, production or sales centers, and service providers to support the main company's customers.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Each independent center (or) subsidiary may have its own business operations cycles, workflows, and business processes.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Given the realities of globalization, enterprises continuously evaluate how to optimize their regional, divisional, and product or manufacturing strategies to support strategic goals and reduce time-to-market while increasing profitability and delivering value.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] With two-tier ERP, the regional distribution, production, or sales centers and service providers continue operating under their own business model—separate from the main company, using their own ERP systems.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Since these smaller companies' processes and workflows are not tied to main company's processes and workflows, they can respond to local business requirements in multiple locations.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] An alternative to a two-tier approach is to use as an ERP system which allows for multiple workflows to be configured for the same function.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] This allows each operation or division to have its own workflow, say for order entry.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] This avoids the need to integrate two ERP systems as all divisions and operations are running within the same ERP system.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems are theoretically based on industry best practices, and their makers intend that organizations deploy them "as is".
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP vendors do offer customers configuration options that let organizations incorporate their own business rules, but gaps in features often remain even after configuration is complete.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP customers have several options to reconcile feature gaps, each with their own pros/cons.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Technical solutions include rewriting part of the delivered software, writing a homegrown module to work within the ERP system, or interfacing to an external system.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] These three options constitute varying degrees of system customization—with the first being the most invasive and costly to maintain.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Alternatively, there are non-technical options such as changing business practices or organizational policies to better match the delivered ERP feature set.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems can be extended with third-party software, often via vendor-supplied interfaces.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Data migration is the process of moving, copying, and restructuring data from an existing system to an enterprise resource planning (ERP) system.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] It is a critical component of a successful implementation and requires thorough planning.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] However, because migration typically occurs near the end of the implementation process, it often receives inadequate attention.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Often, data migration is incomplete because some of the data in the existing system is either incompatible or not needed in the new system.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] As such, the existing system may need to be kept as an archived database to refer back to once the new ERP system is in place.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] The most fundamental advantage of ERP is that the integration of a myriad of business processes saves time and expense.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Management can make decisions faster and with fewer errors.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Data becomes visible across the organization.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Research published in 2011 based on a survey of 225 manufacturers, retailers and distributors found "high" rates of interest and adoption of ERP systems and that very few businesses were "completely untouched" by the concept of an ERP system.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] 27% of the companies survey had a fully operational system, 12% were at that time rolling out a system and 26% had an existing ERP system which they were extending or upgrading.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] The term "postmodern ERP" was coined by Gartner in 2013, when it first appeared in the paper series "Predicts 2014".
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] The basic idea is that there should still be a core ERP solution that would cover most important business functions, while other functions will be covered by specialist software solutions that merely extend the core ERP.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] This concept is similar to the "best-of-breed" approach to software execution, but it shouldn't be confused with it.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] While in both cases, applications that make up the whole are relatively loosely connected and quite easily interchangeable, in the case of the latter there is no ERP solution whatsoever.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] Instead, every business function is covered by a separate software solution.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] There is, however, no golden rule as to what business functions should be part of the core ERP, and what should be covered by supplementary solutions.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] According to Gartner, every company must define their own postmodern ERP strategy, based on company's internal and external needs, operations and processes.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] For example, a company may define that the core ERP solution should cover those business processes that must stay behind the firewall, and therefore, choose to leave their core ERP on-premises.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] At the same time, another company may adopt a hybrid ERP approach, hosting the core ERP solution in the cloud while moving only a few ERP modules as supplementary solutions to on-premises.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] The main benefits that companies will gain from implementing postmodern ERP strategy are speed and flexibility when reacting to unexpected changes in business processes or on the organizational level.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] With the majority of applications having a relatively loose connection, it is fairly easy to replace or upgrade them whenever necessary.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] In addition to that, following the examples above, companies can select and combine cloud-based and on-premises solutions that are most suited for their ERP needs.
[src:purdue-model/enterprise-resource-planning] The downside of postmodern ERP is that it will most likely lead to an increased number of software vendors that companies will have to manage, as well as pose additional integration challenges for the central IT.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] An **industrial control system** (**ICS**) is an electronic control system and associated instrumentation used for industrial process control.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Control systems can range in size from a few modular panel-mounted controllers to large interconnected and interactive distributed control systems (DCSs) with many thousands of field connections.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Control systems receive data from remote sensors measuring process variables (PVs), compare the collected data with desired setpoints (SPs), and derive command functions that are used to control a process through the final control elements (FCEs), such as control valves.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Larger systems are usually implemented by supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) systems, or DCSs, and programmable logic controllers (PLCs), though SCADA and PLC systems are scalable down to small systems with few control loops.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Such systems are extensively used in industries such as chemical processing, pulp and paper manufacture, power generation, oil and gas processing, and telecommunications.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] The simplest control systems are based around small discrete controllers with a single control loop each.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] These are usually panel mounted, which allows direct viewing of the front panel and provides a means of manual intervention by the operator, either to manually control the process or to change control setpoints.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Originally, these would be pneumatic controllers, a few of which are still in use, but nearly all are now electronic.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Quite complex systems can be created with networks of these controllers communicating using industry-standard protocols.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Networking allows the use of local or remote SCADA operator interfaces and enables the cascading and interlocking of controllers.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] However, as the number of control loops increases for a system design, there is a point where the use of a programmable logic controller (PLC) or distributed control system (DCS) is more manageable or cost-effective.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] A distributed control system (DCS) is a digital process control system (PCS) for a process or plant, wherein controller functions and field connection modules are distributed throughout the system.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] As the number of control loops grows, DCS becomes more cost effective than discrete controllers.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Additionally, a DCS provides supervisory viewing and management over large industrial processes.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] In a DCS, a hierarchy of controllers is connected by communication networks, allowing centralized control rooms and local on-plant monitoring and control.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] A DCS enables easy configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and easy interfacing with other computer systems such as production control.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] It also enables more sophisticated alarm handling, introduces automatic event logging, removes the need for physical records such as chart recorders and allows the control equipment to be networked and thereby located locally to the equipment being controlled to reduce cabling.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] A DCS typically uses custom-designed processors as controllers and uses either proprietary interconnections or standard protocols for communication.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Input and output modules form the peripheral components of the system.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] The processors receive information from input modules, process the information and decide control actions to be performed by the output modules.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] The input modules receive information from sensing instruments in the process (or field) and the output modules transmit instructions to the final control elements, such as control valves.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] The field inputs and outputs can either be continuously changing analog signals, e.g., current loop or 2-state signals that switch either *on* or *off*, such as relay contacts or a semiconductor switch.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Distributed control systems can normally also support Foundation Fieldbus, PROFIBUS, HART, Modbus and other digital communication buses that carry not only input and output signals but also advanced messages such as error diagnostics and status signals.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) is a control system architecture that uses computers, networked data communications and graphical user interfaces for high-level process supervisory management.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] The operator interfaces, which enable monitoring and the issuing of process commands, such as controller setpoint changes, are handled through the SCADA supervisory computer system.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] However, the real-time control logic or controller calculations are performed by networked modules which connect to other peripheral devices such as programmable logic controllers and discrete PID controllers which interface to the process plant or machinery.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] The SCADA concept was developed as a universal means of remote access to a variety of local control modules, which could be from different manufacturers, allowing access through standard automation protocols.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] In practice, large SCADA systems have grown to become very similar to distributed control systems in function, but using multiple means of interfacing with the plant.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] They can control large-scale processes that can include multiple sites and work over large distances.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] This is a commonly used architecture industrial control systems, however there are concerns about SCADA systems being vulnerable to cyberwarfare or cyberterrorism attacks.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] The SCADA software operates on a supervisory level as control actions are performed automatically by RTUs or PLCs.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] SCADA control functions are usually restricted to basic overriding or supervisory level intervention.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] A feedback control loop is directly controlled by the RTU or PLC, but the SCADA software monitors the overall performance of the loop.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] For example, a PLC may control the flow of cooling water through part of an industrial process to a set point level, but the SCADA system software will allow operators to change the set points for the flow.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] The SCADA also enables alarm conditions, such as loss of flow or high temperature, to be displayed and recorded.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] PLCs can range from small modular devices with tens of inputs and outputs (I/O) in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with a count of thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] They can be designed for multiple arrangements of digital and analog inputs and outputs, extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Programs to control machine operation are typically stored in battery-backed-up or non-volatile memory.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Process control of large industrial plants has evolved through many stages.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Initially, control was from panels local to the process plant.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] However, this required personnel to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] The next logical development was the transmission of all plant measurements to a permanently staffed central control room.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Often, the controllers were behind the control room panels, and all automatic and manual control outputs were individually transmitted back to the plant in the form of pneumatic or electrical signals.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Effectively, this was the centralisation of all the localised panels, with the advantages of reduced manpower requirements and a consolidated overview of the process.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] However, whilst providing a central control focus, this arrangement was inflexible as each control loop had its own controller hardware, so system changes required reconfiguration of signals by re-piping or re-wiring.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] It also required continual operator movement within a large control room in order to monitor the whole process.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] With the coming of electronic processors, high-speed electronic signalling networks and electronic graphic displays, it became possible to replace these discrete controllers with computer-based algorithms, hosted on a network of input/output racks with their own control processors.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] These could be distributed around the plant and would communicate with the graphic displays in the control room.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] The concept of *distributed control* was realised.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] The introduction of distributed control allowed flexible interconnection and re-configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and interfacing with other production computer systems.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] For large control systems, the general commercial name *distributed control system* (DCS) was coined to refer to proprietary modular systems from many manufacturers that integrated high-speed networking and a full suite of displays and control racks.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] While the DCS was tailored to meet the needs of large continuous industrial processes, in industries where combinatorial and sequential logic was the primary requirement, the PLC evolved out of a need to replace racks of relays and timers used for event-driven control.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] The old controls were difficult to reconfigure and debug, and PLC control enabled networking of signals to a central control area with electronic displays.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] PLCs were first developed for the automotive industry on vehicle production lines, where sequential logic was becoming very complex.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] It was soon adopted in a large number of other event-driven applications as varied as printing presses and water treatment plants.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] SCADA's history is rooted in distribution applications, such as power, natural gas, and water pipelines, where there is a need to gather remote data through potentially unreliable or intermittent low-bandwidth and high-latency links.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] SCADA systems use open-loop control with sites that are widely separated geographically.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] A SCADA system uses remote terminal units (RTUs) to send supervisory data back to a control centre.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Most RTU systems always had some capacity to handle local control while the master station is not available.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] However, over the years, RTU systems have grown more and more capable of handling local control.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] The boundaries between DCS and SCADA/PLC systems are blurring as time goes on.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] The technical limits that drove the designs of these various systems are no longer as much of an issue.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Many PLC platforms can now perform quite well as a small DCS, using remote I/O and are sufficiently reliable that some SCADA systems actually manage closed-loop control over long distances.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] With the increasing speed of today's processors, many DCS products have a full line of PLC-like subsystems that weren't offered when they were initially developed.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] In 1993, with the release of IEC-1131, later to become IEC-61131-3, the industry moved towards increased code standardization with reusable, hardware-independent control software.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] For the first time, object-oriented programming (OOP) became possible within industrial control systems.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] This led to the development of both programmable automation controllers (PAC) and industrial PCs (IPC).
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] These are platforms programmed in the five standardized IEC languages: ladder logic, structured text, function block, instruction list and sequential function chart.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] They can also be programmed in modern high-level languages such as C or C++.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Additionally, they accept models developed in analytical tools such as MATLAB and Simulink.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Unlike traditional PLCs, which use proprietary operating systems, IPCs utilize Windows IoT.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] IPCs have the advantage of powerful multi-core processors with much lower hardware costs than traditional PLCs and fit well into multiple form factors such as DIN rail mount, combined with a touch-screen as a panel PC, or as an embedded PC.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] New hardware platforms and technology have contributed significantly to the evolution of DCS and SCADA systems, further blurring the boundaries and changing definitions.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] SCADA and PLCs are vulnerable to cyber attack.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] Government Joint Capability Technology Demonstration (JCTD) known as MOSAICS (More Situational Awareness for Industrial Control Systems) is the initial demonstration of cybersecurity defensive capability for critical infrastructure control systems.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] MOSAICS addresses the Department of Defense (DOD) operational need for cyber defense capabilities to defend critical infrastructure control systems from cyber attack, such as power, water and wastewater, and safety controls, affect the physical environment.
[src:purdue-model/industrial-control-system] The MOSAICS JCTD prototype will be shared with commercial industry through Industry Days for further research and development, an approach intended to lead to an innovative, game-changing capabilities for cybersecurity for critical infrastructure control systems.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] MES creates the "as-built" record, capturing the data, processes and outcomes of the manufacturing process.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] This can be especially important in regulated industries, such as food and beverage or pharmaceutical, where documentation and proof of processes, events and actions may be required.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] As of 2025, the manufacturing execution systems are shifting from rigid, monolithic on-premise software to modular, cloud-connected platforms.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] "Manufacturing execution systems [help] create flawless manufacturing processes and provide real-time feedback of requirement changes", and provide information at a single source.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] A wide variety of systems arose using collected data for a dedicated purpose.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] Further development of these systems during the 1990s introduced overlap in functionality.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] Then the Manufacturing Enterprise Solutions Association International (MESA) introduced some structure by defining 11 functions that set the scope of MES.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] In 2000, the ANSI/ISA-95 standard merged this model with the Purdue Reference Model (PRM).
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] A functional hierarchy was defined in which MES were situated at Level 3 between ERP at Level 4 and process control at Levels 0, 1, 2.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] With the publication of the third part of the standard in 2005, activities in Level 3 were divided over four main operations: production, quality, logistics and maintenance.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] Between 2005 and 2013, additional or revised parts of the ANSI/ISA-95 standard defined the architecture of an MES into more detail, covering how to internally distribute functionality and what information to exchange internally as well as externally.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] Over the years, international standards and models have refined the scope of such systems in terms of activities.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] MES integrates with ISA-95 (previous Purdue Reference Model, “95”) with multiple relationships.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] The collection of systems acting on the ISA-95 Level 3 can be called manufacturing operations management systems (MOMS).
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] Apart from an MES, there are typically laboratory information management system (LIMS), warehouse management system (WMS) and computerized maintenance management system (CMMS).
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] Examples of systems acting on ISA-95 Level 4 are product lifecycle management (PLM), enterprise resource planning (ERP), customer relationship management (CRM), human resource management (HRM), and process development execution system (PDES).
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] In many cases, middleware enterprise application integration (EAI) systems are being used to exchange transaction messages between MES and Level 4 systems.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] A common data definition, B2MML, has been defined within the ISA-95 standard to link MES systems to these Level 4 systems.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] Systems acting on ISA-95 Level 2 are supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA), programmable logic controllers (PLC), distributed control systems (DCS) and building automation systems (BAS).
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] Most MES systems include connectivity as part of their product offering.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] Direct communication of plant floor equipment data is established by connecting to the PLC.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] Often, plant floor data is first collected and diagnosed for real-time control in a DCS or SCADA system.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] In this case, the MES systems connect to these Level 2 systems for exchanging plant floor data.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] The industry standard for plant floor connectivity has evolved from OLE for Process Control (OPC) to OPC Unified Architecture (OPC-UA).
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] Unlike its predecessor, OPC-UA is platform-independent, allowing it to run on Linux and embedded devices while offering robust security models.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] In modern Industry 4.0 architectures, MES connectivity often extends beyond the traditional hierarchy.
[src:purdue-model/manufacturing-execution-system] Systems increasingly utilize IIoT protocols like MQTT (often with Sparkplug B) to transmit lightweight data to cloud-based analytics platforms, creating a hybrid architecture where OPC-UA handles complex machine data and MQTT handles rapid telemetry.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] The built environment, whether commercial or domestic, is increasingly controlled and monitored via Internet of Things (IoT) and Industrial Internet of Things (IIoT) devices.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] In this application space, these IoT devices are both interconnected via converged technology edge IoT platforms and or via "cloud" based applications.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] Embedded Systems are also included in the sphere of operational technology (e.g. smart instrumentation), along with a large subset of scientific data acquisition, control, and computing devices.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] Systems that process operational data (including electronic, telecommunications, computer systems and technical components) are included under the term operational technology.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] OT systems can be required to control valves, engines, conveyors and other machines to regulate various process values, such as temperature, pressure, flow, and to monitor them to prevent hazardous conditions.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] OT systems use various technologies for hardware design and communications protocols, that are unknown in IT.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] Common problems include supporting legacy systems & devices and numerous vendor architectures and standards.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] Since OT systems often supervise industrial processes, most of the time availability must be sustained.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] This often means that real time (or near-real time) processing is required, with high rates of reliability and availability.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] This kind of environment may also be referred to as industrial information technology (IIT).
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] Historical OT networks utilized proprietary protocols optimized for the required functions, some of which have become adopted as 'standard' industrial communications protocols (e.g.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] DNP3, Modbus, Profibus, LonWorks, DALI, BACnet, KNX, EnOcean and OPC-UA).
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] More recently IT-standard network protocols are being implemented in OT devices and systems to reduce complexity and increase compatibility with more traditional IT hardware (e.g.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] TCP/IP); this however has had a demonstrable reduction in security for OT systems, which in the past have relied on air gaps and the inability to run PC-based malware (see Stuxnet for a well-known example of this change).
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] The term operational technology as applied to industrial control systems was first published in a research paper from Gartner in May 2006 (Steenstrup, Sumic, Spiers, Williams) and presented publicly in September 2006 at the Gartner Energy and Utilities IT Summit.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] Initially the term was applied to power utility control systems, but over time was adopted by other industrial sectors and used in combination with IoT.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] A principal driver of the adoption of the term was that the nature of operational technology platforms had evolved from bespoke proprietary systems to complex software portfolios that rely on IT infrastructure.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] This change was termed IT OT convergence.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] The concept of aligning and integrating the IT and OT systems of industrial companies gained importance as companies realized that physical assets and infrastructure was both managed by OT systems but also generated data for the IT systems running the business.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] Industrial technology companies such as GE, Hitachi, Honeywell, Siemens, ABB and Rockwell are the main providers of OT platforms and systems either embedded in equipment or added to them for control, management and monitoring.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] These industrial technology companies have needed to evolve into software companies rather than being strictly machine providers.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] Security of operational technology systems has historically relied almost entirely on the standalone nature of OT installations, security by obscurity.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] At least since 2005 OT systems have become linked to IT systems with the corporate goal of widening an organization's ability to monitor and adjust its OT systems, which has introduced massive challenges in securing them.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] Approaches known from regular IT are usually replaced or redesigned to align with the OT environment.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] The intersection of operational technology and standard networking infrastructure exposes industrial processes to several distinct categories of risk.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] Mitigation of these integrated risks typically involves the adoption of multi-layered security frameworks, continuous anomaly monitoring, and adherence to established institutional standards such as the ISA/IEC 62443 series.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] Operational technology is widely used in refineries, power plants, nuclear plants, etc. and as such has become a common, crucial element of critical infrastructure systems.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] Depending on the country, critical infrastructure operators may face increasing legal obligations with regard to the implementation of OT systems.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] For several decades, hundreds of thousands of buildings have been upgraded with IoT building management, automation and smart lighting control solutions, but many of these solutions lack the proper security measures.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] This has recently led to bad actors exploiting such solutions' vulnerabilities with ransomware attacks causing system lock outs, operational failures exposing businesses operating in such buildings to the immense risks to health and safety, operations, brand reputation and financial damage.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] There is a strong focus put on subjects like IT/OT cooperation or IT/OT alignment in the modern industrial setting.
[src:purdue-model/operational-technology] The Stuxnet malware is one example of this, highlighting the potential for disaster should a safety system become infected with malware (whether targeted at that system or accidentally infected).
[src:purdue-model/purdue-enterprise-reference-architecture] PERA is a reference architecture that can model the enterprise in multiple layers and in multiple stages of the architectural life cycle.
